of these 'followers'-including whether they can and do challenge the policies and strategies or the core position of the hegemon. Through the analysis of both historical and contemporary cases that feature global and regional hegemons in Europe, Latin America, the Middle East, Africa, Asia, and South Asia, and that address a range of interest areas-from political, to economic and military-the book reveals the domestic and international factors that account for the motivations and actions of weaker states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aGreat powers. 0aHegemony. 0aInternational relations. 0aStates, Small. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 0aWorld politicsy1989- 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aJesse, Neal G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLobell, Steven E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilliams, Kristen P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478110740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804781107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804781107.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles